WEBVTT

00:01.710 --> 00:05.589
♪

00:34.326 --> 00:36.578
‐ Hey, can I talk to you for a‐‐

00:36.578 --> 00:38.539
Oh...

00:38.539 --> 00:40.165
Hey.
‐ Hey.

00:42.251 --> 00:43.544
‐ What's up?

00:43.544 --> 00:47.673
‐ Uh, can you go to Mia's
dad's wedding with me?

00:47.673 --> 00:49.675
‐ Aw! That's sweet of you to ask.

00:49.675 --> 00:52.094
Hard pass.
‐ What? Why?

00:52.094 --> 00:54.596
‐ Let's see, all of your friends
are painfully boring,

00:54.596 --> 00:58.559
and I couldn't pick Mia's dad and Veronica
out of a line‐up of old people.

00:59.184 --> 01:02.813
‐ Pilar, please. I feel really bad
for showing up solo last second.

01:04.898 --> 01:08.735
Why don't you bring Rahim?
He loves all that cheesy romantic crap,

01:08.735 --> 01:10.404
he's always trying to start a conga line,

01:10.404 --> 01:14.783
and he has fancy blazer napkins
for every suit he owns.

01:14.783 --> 01:18.161
‐ Do you not know the term
"pocket square"?

01:18.161 --> 01:20.664
‐ I'm just saying,
you two would have fun together.

01:23.333 --> 01:25.377
‐ I mean, there's like,
it's like zero pressure, but,

01:25.377 --> 01:26.920
w‐would you wanna go?

01:26.920 --> 01:28.797
‐ Are you sure Benji'd be cool with it?

01:28.797 --> 01:32.009
‐ Honestly, Benji kind of lost his right
to an opinion

01:32.009 --> 01:34.219
when he bailed on me last second.

01:34.219 --> 01:37.264
And besides, we're friends.
Why wouldn't he be cool with it?

01:39.057 --> 01:42.227
‐ Yeah. Okay. Yes.
I would love to go with you.

01:43.520 --> 01:46.106
‐ All right. Cool. Felix is meeting us
here around three o'clock.

01:46.106 --> 01:47.858
‐ See you then.
‐ All right. See you then.

01:49.359 --> 01:51.904
‐ ♪ Somebody to tell me
it'll be all right ♪

01:51.904 --> 01:54.823
♪ Somebody to tell me
it'll be just fine ♪

01:54.823 --> 01:57.951
♪ If someone has been there before,
say it right now ♪

01:57.951 --> 02:00.913
♪ 'Cause I just need to hear it ♪

02:02.331 --> 02:05.626
♪

02:06.335 --> 02:10.714
‐ Well, I'm off to show my new listing.

02:10.714 --> 02:13.926
The house was the site
of a pretty grisly murder.

02:13.926 --> 02:16.595
I'm trying to distract with my cleavage.

02:16.595 --> 02:18.805
‐ I would totally buy a
murder house from you.

02:18.805 --> 02:21.683
‐ Aw! I'll see you at my place tonight?

02:21.683 --> 02:25.354
‐ Yeah.
‐ I'm making fried chicken,
so have a light lunch.

02:25.354 --> 02:27.814
And wear some loose pants.
‐ I'll be there.

02:27.814 --> 02:29.525
‐ Mmm.
‐ Mmm.

02:29.525 --> 02:31.068
[knocking on door]

02:33.987 --> 02:36.156
ISABEL:
Oh. Hi.

02:37.366 --> 02:40.702
‐ Hi. I'm‐‐
‐ Shelby. Right?

02:41.537 --> 02:43.539
‐ Isa. Uh, what are you doing here?

02:43.539 --> 02:46.667
‐ Sorry. I just‐‐ I need to talk
and you're not answering my texts.

02:46.667 --> 02:49.962
‐ Isn't he the absolute worst
with texting? [laughs]

02:49.962 --> 02:51.713
‐ Mm‐hmm.

02:51.713 --> 02:54.716
‐ All right, well, I was just
heading out, so, um...

02:54.716 --> 02:56.718
It's nice to meet you, Isabel.

02:56.718 --> 02:57.761
‐ You, too.

03:03.433 --> 03:05.602
[door closes]
‐ You want a donut, or‐‐

03:05.602 --> 03:07.771
‐ I'm sorry. I didn't know she'd be here.

03:07.771 --> 03:11.316
I just... I'm worried about Victor.

03:11.316 --> 03:15.112
He's barely left his room since
his "break" with Benji.

03:15.112 --> 03:18.407
Which I know was at least
partially my fault.

03:18.407 --> 03:21.702
I was pretty horrible to that boy.
‐ Well...

03:21.702 --> 03:24.371
It's never too late to be un‐horrible.

03:24.997 --> 03:27.040
‐ Yeah. Maybe you're right.

03:28.750 --> 03:31.920
But it's not just Benji.

03:31.920 --> 03:33.964
When Victor saw you with Shelby...

03:33.964 --> 03:36.258
‐ Yeah, I know.
I, I could tell it really got to him.

03:37.593 --> 03:40.470
‐ Mando, we've been separated
for six months.

03:40.470 --> 03:42.598
And you're seeing another woman. It's‐‐

03:43.891 --> 03:46.185
I believe we can save our marriage.

03:46.935 --> 03:49.438
I want to save our marriage.

03:51.106 --> 03:53.108
But if you don't,

03:53.108 --> 03:56.528
then it's time to start this new chapter
in our lives.

03:58.947 --> 04:01.491
This living in between is just...

04:01.491 --> 04:03.869
it's too hard on the kids.

04:03.869 --> 04:05.579
It's too hard on me.

04:07.706 --> 04:10.542
It's time for you to decide
what you want to do.

04:13.629 --> 04:15.964
‐ I know. You're right.

04:20.385 --> 04:22.221
‐ Thanks for the donut.

04:23.680 --> 04:27.476
[door opens, then closes]

04:34.316 --> 04:35.317
[doorbell rings]

04:47.412 --> 04:49.414
‐ Hi, sweetheart.

04:49.414 --> 04:51.750
‐ Hi, Mom.

04:53.085 --> 04:54.336
‐ Hi.

04:55.796 --> 04:57.673
‐ Welcome home.
‐ Oh...

04:58.924 --> 05:00.884
‐ I missed you.
‐ I missed you.

05:01.677 --> 05:03.011
I swear to you,

05:03.011 --> 05:05.722
this woman truly believed

05:05.722 --> 05:08.267
that she was the lost sister
of the Queen of England.

05:08.267 --> 05:11.395
And when people would pass by her,
they would have to curtsy,

05:11.395 --> 05:13.146
or she would just lose it.

05:13.146 --> 05:14.314
[laughs]

05:15.858 --> 05:17.651
‐ It seems like you're doing good, Mom.

05:17.651 --> 05:18.986
‐ I feel good.

05:18.986 --> 05:24.074
I mean, not that there weren't
tough days, but...

05:24.074 --> 05:28.954
when it would get hard, I would just...
[sighs]

05:28.954 --> 05:31.498
close my eyes, I would take a deep breath,

05:31.498 --> 05:36.420
and I would think about all the things
that I would miss

05:36.420 --> 05:38.130
if I didn't get my shit together.

05:39.756 --> 05:42.676
Like having brunch with you...

05:43.635 --> 05:45.470
Seeing you graduate.

05:47.598 --> 05:49.057
Seeing you get married.

05:50.559 --> 05:52.394
And that made it

05:52.394 --> 05:55.606
clear as day what I needed to do.

05:56.523 --> 06:00.027
So I would drag my ass out of bed,

06:00.027 --> 06:02.613
I would take my new meds...

06:04.114 --> 06:07.409
I would curse that place for not allowing
me to have Swedish Fish,

06:07.409 --> 06:09.912
because, like... [scoffs]

06:09.912 --> 06:11.747
And then I would go to therapy.

06:15.042 --> 06:17.252
‐ You know, Mom,
I can bail on the wedding.

06:17.252 --> 06:19.588
‐ No. No, you should go,

06:19.588 --> 06:23.342
and I don't think that Lake would
take kindly to you standing her up.

06:23.342 --> 06:24.635
[laughs]

06:26.178 --> 06:28.889
‐ Yeah, um...

06:28.889 --> 06:31.391
I was gonna tell you about that

06:31.391 --> 06:33.727
once, uh, you got back up on your feet.

06:33.727 --> 06:37.606
Um, Lake and I broke up.

06:37.606 --> 06:40.734
‐ Oh, Felix, I'm so sorry.

06:40.734 --> 06:42.152
What happened?

06:42.152 --> 06:44.404
‐ She betrayed my trust.

06:45.405 --> 06:48.909
I mean, she told her mom
about our situation.

06:48.909 --> 06:51.662
‐ I understand why you feel betrayed.

06:54.581 --> 06:57.668
But I want you to know that

06:57.668 --> 07:00.879
whatever happens between you
and Lake in the future,

07:00.879 --> 07:03.590
I will forever be grateful to her.

07:05.259 --> 07:06.844
‐ What do you mean?

07:07.427 --> 07:12.349
‐ She risked your relationship to make
sure that I got the help that I needed.

07:13.475 --> 07:17.646
And I think that that makes her
pretty special.

07:19.398 --> 07:23.527
Plus, that girl looks great in a crop top.

07:24.236 --> 07:25.654
‐ Yeah.

07:25.654 --> 07:27.364
‐ Okay, so which one of these says,

07:27.364 --> 07:30.450
"Lake Meriwether is single
and ready to mingle?"

07:30.450 --> 07:32.035
[laughs]

07:32.035 --> 07:35.372
Who am I kidding? It's the jumpsuit.
It's always the jumpsuit.

07:35.372 --> 07:38.458
‐ Look, I'm so glad that you are
ready to mingle,

07:38.458 --> 07:40.711
but I only invited like
four people to this wedding,

07:40.711 --> 07:44.006
and they're either gay,
my boyfriend or your ex‐boyfriend.

07:44.006 --> 07:45.883
[door opens]
HAROLD: Morning, ladies.

07:45.883 --> 07:46.842
‐ Good morning.

07:46.842 --> 07:49.803
‐ Dad! Isn't the groom not
supposed to see the bride

07:49.803 --> 07:51.722
before the wedding?
‐ Ah, well...

07:51.722 --> 07:54.266
‐ I think when the bride
is hugely pregnant,

07:54.266 --> 07:56.310
all the traditional rules
kind of go out the window.

07:56.310 --> 07:58.520
WOMAN: Excuse me, Mr. Brooks?
‐ Oh. Excuse me, ladies.

07:59.271 --> 08:00.814
VERONICA: Hi!
HAROLD: Hey.

08:02.858 --> 08:04.151
‐ Uh...

08:05.777 --> 08:07.738
This is for you.

08:07.738 --> 08:09.198
‐ Mia!

08:11.658 --> 08:14.328
Oh, it's beautiful!

08:14.328 --> 08:17.706
‐ Yeah, it was my grandmother's.
And I know she would have loved you.

08:17.706 --> 08:20.667
Except for you being knocked up.
And white.

08:21.585 --> 08:24.129
Yeah, actually,
she probably would've hated you.

08:24.129 --> 08:26.340
[both laugh]
But I‐‐ I like you,

08:26.340 --> 08:29.051
and I, I thought it
could be your something old.

08:29.051 --> 08:31.178
‐ I love it.

08:31.178 --> 08:33.514
‐ I'm really glad we're gonna be a family.

08:33.514 --> 08:35.098
[laughs]
‐ Oh.

08:39.311 --> 08:40.812
Um...

08:42.481 --> 08:44.733
I'm sorry. Harold...

08:46.026 --> 08:47.444
‐ Yeah.
‐ I'm sorry, we can't‐‐

08:47.444 --> 08:49.905
‐ I know. I know.

08:49.905 --> 08:51.740
‐ Guys, what's going on?

08:53.200 --> 08:56.328
‐ Hey, uh, sweetheart, listen, um...

08:56.328 --> 08:57.287
[exhales sharply]

08:59.373 --> 09:02.459
I'm gonna go ahead
and take the job at Stanford.

09:03.836 --> 09:06.213
‐ What? I thought you turned it down.

09:06.213 --> 09:08.882
HAROLD:
I know, but you know what, sweetheart?

09:08.882 --> 09:11.718
I realized it's too big of an opportunity.

09:13.095 --> 09:15.097
Now, I was gonna tell you.

09:15.097 --> 09:17.474
I just...

09:17.474 --> 09:20.143
wanted today to be perfect for all of us.

09:22.604 --> 09:24.439
‐ Okay.

09:24.439 --> 09:28.485
‐ Hey, Mia, come on. Look, let's just
talk about this for a second. Okay?

09:28.485 --> 09:29.903
‐ I mean, there's nothing to talk about.

09:29.903 --> 09:32.531
And I'm so stupid for thinking
that there ever was.

09:44.418 --> 09:46.044
[knocking on door]

09:48.881 --> 09:50.299
‐ Oh, hey.

09:51.175 --> 09:52.342
‐ Hi.

09:53.385 --> 09:56.221
‐ Uh, I'll tell Victor you're here.

09:56.221 --> 09:58.223
Victor, Felix is here!

10:01.018 --> 10:04.688
‐ So, uh, my mom, she got out
of the hospital this morning.

10:04.688 --> 10:06.315
Yeah, she's doing really good.

10:06.315 --> 10:07.733
‐ That's awesome.

10:07.733 --> 10:10.736
‐ Yeah, you know,
I didn't, uh, really know what to expect.

10:10.736 --> 10:12.738
Part of me was scared she'd be on
a ton of meds

10:12.738 --> 10:15.282
and a completely different person.

10:15.282 --> 10:18.619
But, uh, then I saw her‐‐
‐ Felix. I can't do this.

10:18.619 --> 10:20.913
I'm really glad that
your mom is doing better,

10:20.913 --> 10:24.333
but I can't just pretend that
everything between us is normal

10:24.333 --> 10:26.543
after I kissed you.

10:26.543 --> 10:27.794
‐ Okay.

10:29.254 --> 10:33.842
‐ I like you. And you don't like me back.
Which is fine.

10:33.842 --> 10:37.888
But I think it's best if you go back to
being Victor's nerdy best friend.

10:37.888 --> 10:40.766
And I go back to being his moody sister.

10:42.100 --> 10:45.145
And we'll say "hi" sometimes
when we see each other at school,

10:45.145 --> 10:49.274
or when we're taking out the trash
or whatever. But that's it.

10:52.110 --> 10:53.487
VICTOR:
Hey!

10:57.824 --> 10:58.909
You okay?

10:59.952 --> 11:02.120
‐ I'm, I'm good. Yeah, but...

11:02.120 --> 11:04.790
Not as good as you. I mean the‐‐

11:04.790 --> 11:08.168
the tie, the hair, the face.
I mean, hot damn potato chip!

11:08.168 --> 11:09.711
[laughs]
RAHIM: Knock, knock.

11:10.587 --> 11:14.758
FELIX:
Good God, you two.
Give the rest of us a chance.

11:15.676 --> 11:17.135
‐ You do look really good.

11:17.135 --> 11:19.054
‐ You clean up pretty well yourself,
Salazar.

11:19.054 --> 11:21.598
‐ Okay, if someone doesn't give me
a compliment about how I look,

11:21.598 --> 11:23.141
I'm not going.
[both chuckle]

11:23.141 --> 11:26.812
‐ Come on. We've got a wedding to get to.

11:26.812 --> 11:28.272
You look great.

11:28.272 --> 11:32.609
♪ cello music playing ♪

11:32.609 --> 11:34.862
[indistinct chatter]

11:39.366 --> 11:41.660
‐ Don't worry. We'll figure this out.

11:41.660 --> 11:45.455
‐ No, we won't.
But thank you for saying that.

11:49.042 --> 11:50.752
CATER WAITER:
Sparkling lemonade?

11:51.628 --> 11:52.838
LAKE:
Lucy.

11:52.838 --> 11:55.132
Hey! I didn't know you'd be here.

11:55.132 --> 11:57.593
‐ I'm not a guest. I'm a cater waiter.

11:57.593 --> 11:59.261
Hence the super cool bow tie.

11:59.261 --> 12:02.014
‐ Well, you are rocking the hell
out of that bow tie.

12:02.014 --> 12:03.348
[distant chattering]

12:05.934 --> 12:08.187
Oh, God. There's Felix.

12:09.313 --> 12:11.648
He looks super cute in that little vest.

12:11.648 --> 12:13.650
‐ I thought you guys broke up.

12:13.650 --> 12:15.485
‐ No, we did.

12:15.485 --> 12:19.781
I might not be as single and
ready to mingle as I'm pretending to be.

12:24.036 --> 12:26.872
‐ If my boss asks, you're thirty‐four.

12:26.872 --> 12:28.332
[laughs]

12:36.298 --> 12:37.841
‐ Is this seat taken?

12:39.343 --> 12:42.095
‐ No. No, you, you look, uh, beautiful.

12:43.096 --> 12:44.389
‐ Thank you.

12:46.099 --> 12:47.601
Where's Benji?

12:49.144 --> 12:51.772
‐ Victor and Benji are on a break.

12:52.898 --> 12:56.235
‐ Wow, Victor wasted no time at all.

12:56.235 --> 12:57.903
‐ They're just friends.

12:57.903 --> 13:01.782
‐ Please. "Just friends" is for two fives.
Not a pair of nines.

13:06.578 --> 13:11.333
♪

13:16.380 --> 13:20.384
HAROLD
I vow to always be your best friend.

13:20.384 --> 13:24.263
I vow to always put your happiness first,

13:24.263 --> 13:26.056
and my ambitions second.

13:27.474 --> 13:30.561
VERONICA
I know there will be tough days.

13:30.561 --> 13:34.773
It's on those days that
I vow to love you the hardest.

13:34.773 --> 13:39.695
HAROLD:
I vow to always remember
that we are worth fighting for.

13:39.695 --> 13:42.739
Forever. No matter what.

13:43.949 --> 13:45.492
VERONICA:
No matter what.

13:45.492 --> 13:49.621
♪ upbeat music plays over speakers ♪

13:54.459 --> 13:56.545
[door closes]
ISABEL: Hi.

13:59.965 --> 14:03.260
I think it's about time
you and I had a little talk.

14:10.100 --> 14:13.437
‐ So, to what do I owe the pleasure?

14:13.437 --> 14:17.274
‐ Uh, actually,
I wanted to bring you something.

14:19.860 --> 14:21.278
[chuckles]

14:21.278 --> 14:23.780
‐ A Tupperware of some chicken?

14:23.780 --> 14:25.532
‐ It's my pollo guisado.

14:25.532 --> 14:27.618
It's what we were supposed to have
for dinner that night

14:27.618 --> 14:29.036
before the first day of school.

14:29.036 --> 14:31.079
‐ I remember.

14:31.079 --> 14:33.248
‐ I am sorry that I ruined that night.

14:35.167 --> 14:37.586
I'm sorry for a lot of things, Benji.

14:37.586 --> 14:39.671
But most of all,

14:39.671 --> 14:44.051
I am sorry if I'm the cause of problems
between you and Victor.

14:46.678 --> 14:49.973
‐ Mmm. Thank you for saying that.

14:49.973 --> 14:52.893
‐ Please don't let me be the reason

14:52.893 --> 14:55.229
that it doesn't work out between you two.

14:57.314 --> 15:00.943
‐ [sighs] Okay‐‐
I appreciate you coming here.

15:02.027 --> 15:05.322
But our problems are bigger than just you.

15:07.658 --> 15:10.744
Too big for a couple of sixteen‐year‐olds,
that's for sure.

15:10.744 --> 15:12.454
‐ Hey.

15:12.454 --> 15:16.083
All relationships have problems,
whether you're sixteen or forty‐‐

15:17.501 --> 15:19.086
Thirty‐nine.

15:19.086 --> 15:22.923
What matters is how hard
you're willing to work at it.

15:22.923 --> 15:26.426
How much of yourself you're willing
to put into it.

15:27.928 --> 15:31.390
And I've never seen Victor
put more of himself into anything.

15:32.933 --> 15:34.434
He even stood up to me.

15:34.434 --> 15:37.479
For the first time in his life.

15:37.479 --> 15:42.734
And we all know that Victor is the world's
biggest mama's boy. [laughs]

15:42.734 --> 15:46.196
But he put our whole relationship
on the line to defend you.

15:47.656 --> 15:49.658
That's how much he loves you.

15:51.869 --> 15:55.205
Anyway, I just needed you
to know all of that.

15:58.542 --> 16:02.713
Oh. Reheat that at 350 for twenty minutes.

16:02.713 --> 16:04.715
Don't you dare put it in the microwave.

16:08.969 --> 16:13.098
VICTOR:
Oh. I don't know if this is for me.
It looks so... creamy.

16:13.098 --> 16:15.976
‐ I know, but YOLO. On three.

16:15.976 --> 16:19.730
One, two, three.
‐ Clink!

16:21.231 --> 16:22.774
[gulps]
VICTOR: Oh, my God.

16:23.483 --> 16:26.195
‐ Yeah, I don't like that. Mmm‐mmm.
‐ I don't see the appeal.

16:27.654 --> 16:30.115
But they're really expensive,
so we should probably have some more.

16:30.115 --> 16:31.491
‐ [laughs] No.

16:32.451 --> 16:35.913
‐ Thank you for inviting me.
I'm having a great time.

16:36.622 --> 16:38.081
‐ Me, too.

16:38.665 --> 16:40.792
‐ You know, you could always live with me.

16:40.792 --> 16:43.587
House is pretty big,
you're pretty small...

16:49.426 --> 16:51.595
‐ Hey, kids. Do you mind if I cut in?

16:52.763 --> 16:53.972
ANDREW: No.

16:53.972 --> 16:55.140
‐ Thanks.

16:58.435 --> 16:59.937
[awkward chuckle]

17:05.817 --> 17:08.946
‐ I can't do this.
‐ Hey, Mia, please. Just wait‐‐

17:11.532 --> 17:13.033
[sighs]

17:15.577 --> 17:16.828
She'll come around.

17:18.455 --> 17:20.874
‐ Mr. Brooks.
Listen, you don't know this,

17:20.874 --> 17:23.710
but I have always
respected the hell out of you.

17:23.710 --> 17:27.840
Your drive, your success, the way
your suits always fit just right.

17:27.840 --> 17:31.301
When I was younger,
I'd always think, "Man,

17:31.301 --> 17:34.680
I want a big, impressive life,
like Harold Brooks."

17:34.680 --> 17:36.723
‐ I appreciate that.

17:36.723 --> 17:40.435
‐ But when Mia told me today what you did,

17:40.435 --> 17:42.980
for the first time ever,
I lost some respect for you.

17:44.314 --> 17:45.983
‐ Well, I'm very sorry to hear that.

17:46.942 --> 17:50.696
‐ Harold, you and I both know
that Mia never fully recovered

17:50.696 --> 17:52.990
from her mother leaving.

17:52.990 --> 17:57.828
It is a miracle that she is the strong,
happy person that she is today.

17:59.079 --> 18:00.873
But you doing this,

18:00.873 --> 18:05.961
ripping her away from her home,
from her friends, from me...

18:07.963 --> 18:09.923
I don't think she'll ever
come back from that.

18:11.300 --> 18:13.051
All right? And that'll be on you.

18:20.726 --> 18:23.312
[phone jingling]

18:27.357 --> 18:29.401
‐ Hi.
‐ Hey.

18:30.777 --> 18:34.239
I just wanted to tell you that
I stopped by Brasstown earlier.

18:34.239 --> 18:36.867
‐ Oh, yeah?
‐ Yeah.

18:36.867 --> 18:39.620
And I did my best
to be un‐horrible to Benji.

18:40.829 --> 18:43.290
